If you happen to have Windows 10, the easiest way to log on is to install the Bash Ubuntu subsystem into Windows. But once you do that, you should you should be able to install that and then you'll be able to use the bash terminal which is very similar to the terminal that is actually built into the the myth computers itself. So this is the method I would suggest if you happen to be on Windows 10 this is a great way to do it. What you do when you have it loaded you just go to the search and you type bash b a s h or Ubuntu and when you click on that it pulls up a window that looks like this and from here we are going to use the SSH command which is the secure shell and it's built into the window here and you just type SSH and then your SUNET ID, mine happens to be CGreg and you type the @symbolandmiff.stanford.edu and you hit enter. And the first time you connect it will ask you if you are sure you want to continue connecting and you should type yes and then it will ask for your password. This is a security feature, it allows you to type your password without somebody who's looking over your shoulder to see it and, it's a nice feature. Anyway, you type that in and then it brings you down to, the actual prompt. As I said, this is the preferred method because it's once you set it up, it's all built into Windows and it's kinda nice. You can do that, but there's another way too. And if you use that program, you just type secure CRT and then, you click on it and a little window comes up. It actually prepopulates a couple of, different Stanford campuses, Stanford campus computer systems. We are gonna use a third one, called NIF. So what you do is you click on new session here. You can leave the port the same, no firewall, and then you type your username. Okay and that's it and then for the secure FX protocol that's fine too and then you can just leave it at myth.stanford. If you want and there you go. Unfortunately, this doesn't allow fancy colors it looks like, which is too bad but you can still use the clear, you can use the reset, the CD command, LS command and so forth you are logged on officially. And that's how you do it. To log out just type log out or control D and that's that. And if you want to click again you can just do that. So that's that. How you log on. Thanks.
